(44, 21, 6, 43, 7, 53, 53, 'returned home again', 'Departure and Return Home', 'Both passages emphasize the act of leaving and returning home. In Acts, the individuals take ship after saying farewell, while in John, every man goes to his own house, highlighting a similar theme of departure.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 6, 43, 16, 32, 32, NULL, 'Scattering and Departure Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of departure and scattering. In Acts, the phrase ''took leave'' reflects the physical separation of individuals, while in John, the scattering of disciples signifies emotional and spiritual separation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 6, 47, 2, 13, 13, NULL, 'Departure and Leaving Connections', 'Both passages emphasize the act of taking leave, indicating a transition or movement from one place to another. This connection highlights the theme of departure in the journeys of the apostles.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 7, 58, 13, 24, 24, 'saluted the brethren', 'Salutation and Community Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of greeting and acknowledging fellow believers. Acts 21:7 mentions saluting the brethren, while Hebrews 13:24 encourages saluting all those in leadership and the saints.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 7, 9, 10, 4, 4, 'saluted the brethren', 'Salutation and Hospitality', 'This connection highlights the theme of greeting and hospitality in both passages. In Acts, the brethren are saluted, while in 1 Samuel, individuals salute and offer bread, emphasizing communal bonds.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 7, 9, 13, 10, 10, 'saluted the brethren', 'Salutation and Fellowship', 'This connection highlights the act of greeting or saluting fellow believers. Both passages emphasize the importance of community and fellowship in their respective contexts.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 7, 40, 5, 47, 47, NULL, 'Salutation and Brotherhood', 'This connection highlights the theme of saluting brethren in both passages. Acts 21:7 mentions saluting the brethren, while Matthew 5:47 questions the value of saluting only one''s brethren.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 7, 44, 12, 20, 20, 'Tyre', 'Connection between Tyre and Ptolemais', 'Both passages mention Tyre, highlighting its significance in the early church and its political relations. The mention of Tyre in Acts 21:7 as a place of fellowship connects to the political dynamics described in Acts 12:20.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 7, 44, 18, 22, 22, 'saluted the brethren', 'Travel and Church Salutation', 'Both passages emphasize the act of greeting or saluting the church upon arrival in a new location. This connection highlights the importance of community and fellowship in the early church as the apostles traveled.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 8, 44, 6, 5, 5, 'Philip the evangelist, which was one of the seven', 'Connection of Philip the Evangelist', 'Both passages emphasize Philip''s role as one of the seven chosen men. This connection highlights his significance in the early church and his continued ministry.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 8, 44, 8, 26, 40, 'Philip the evangelist', 'Philip''s Ministry in Cesarea', 'Both passages emphasize Philip''s role as an evangelist. In Acts 21:8, Philip is identified as ''Philip the evangelist,'' while Acts 8:26-40 details his significant evangelistic encounter with the Ethiopian eunuch, showcasing his ministry''s impact.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 8, 49, 4, 11, 11, 'Philip the evangelist', 'Connection of Evangelists', 'This connection highlights the role of evangelists in the early church. Philip, identified as an evangelist in Acts, exemplifies the ministry mentioned in Ephesians.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 8, 44, 8, 5, 13, 'Philip the evangelist', 'Philip the Evangelist Connection', 'This connection highlights the role of Philip as an evangelist in both passages. In Acts 21:8, he is identified as ''Philip the evangelist,'' while Acts 8:5-13 details his significant ministry in Samaria, emphasizing his preaching and miraculous works.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 8, 55, 4, 5, 5, 'Philip the evangelist', 'Connection of Evangelism', 'This connection highlights the role of evangelism in both passages. Philip is identified as an evangelist in Acts, while Timothy is encouraged to do the work of an evangelist in 2 Timothy.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 8, 44, 9, 30, 30, 'Cesarea', 'Connection through Cesarea', 'Both passages emphasize Cesarea as a significant location in the early church. In Acts 21:8, Paul visits Philip in Cesarea, while Acts 9:30 mentions the sending of Paul from Cesarea to Tarsus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 9, 44, 2, 17, 17, NULL, 'Connection of Prophecy and Daughters', 'Both passages emphasize the role of daughters in prophesying, highlighting a shared theme of prophetic activity among women. Acts 21:9 specifically mentions daughters who prophesy, while Acts 2:17 includes daughters in the broader promise of prophecy in the last days.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 9, 66, 2, 20, 20, 'which did prophesy', 'Prophetic Roles of Women', 'This connection highlights the role of women in prophecy, contrasting the positive depiction of the daughters who prophesy with the negative portrayal of Jezebel as a false prophetess. Both passages emphasize the significance of prophetic voices among women, albeit in different contexts.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 9, 2, 15, 20, 20, 'which did prophesy', 'Women in Prophetic Roles', 'This connection highlights the role of women as prophets in both passages. Acts mentions daughters who prophesy, while Exodus features Miriam as a prophetess leading women in celebration.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 9, 29, 2, 28, 28, NULL, 'Prophecy and Gender in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the role of daughters in prophecy. Acts mentions daughters who prophesy, while Joel foretells that daughters shall prophesy as part of a broader outpouring of the Spirit.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 9, 42, 2, 36, 36, 'which did prophesy', 'Prophetesses in the New Testament', 'Both passages emphasize women who prophesy, highlighting their roles as prophetesses. Acts mentions four daughters who prophesy, while Luke introduces Anna, a prophetess, linking their prophetic gifts.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 9, 7, 4, 4, 4, 'which did prophesy', 'Women in Prophetic Roles', 'This connection highlights the presence of women who prophesy in both passages. Acts mentions four daughters who prophesy, while Judges introduces Deborah, a prophetess.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 9, 12, 22, 14, 14, 'which did prophesy', 'Women in Prophetic Roles', 'Both passages emphasize women who prophesy, highlighting their roles in conveying God''s messages. Acts mentions four daughters who prophesy, while 2 Kings refers to Huldah the prophetess, illustrating the significance of female prophets in biblical narratives.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 10, 44, 11, 28, 28, 'a certain prophet, named Agabus', 'Connection of Agabus the Prophet', 'Both passages emphasize the role of Agabus as a prophet. In Acts 11:28, he predicts a famine, while in Acts 21:10, he is identified again as a prophet, linking his prophetic ministry across different events.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 10, 44, 21, 4, 4, NULL, 'Prophetic Warnings to Paul', 'Both passages emphasize prophetic messages regarding Paul''s journey. In Acts 21:4, disciples warn Paul through the Spirit, while in Acts 21:10, the prophet Agabus further confirms the danger awaiting him in Jerusalem.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 10, 44, 20, 16, 16, NULL, 'Paul''s Journey to Jerusalem', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s determination to reach Jerusalem. In Acts 20:16, Paul hastens to be in Jerusalem for Pentecost, while Acts 21:10 introduces Agabus, a prophet who speaks to Paul about his journey there.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 10, 44, 21, 7, 7, NULL, 'Journey and Prophetic Warning', 'Both passages emphasize the journey of Paul and his companions. The arrival in Ptolemais sets the stage for the subsequent prophetic warning by Agabus in Judea.', 'theme', 0.3, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 11, 44, 21, 33, 33, NULL, 'Binding of Paul', 'This connection highlights the theme of binding, as both passages describe Paul being bound. In Acts 21:11, it is prophesied that he will be bound by the Jews, and in Acts 21:33, he is physically bound with chains by the chief captain.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 11, 9, 15, 27, 28, NULL, 'Binding and Kingdom Transfer', 'This connection highlights the theme of binding and loss of authority. In Acts, Paul is bound, foreshadowing his delivery to Gentiles, while in 1 Samuel, the tearing of the mantle symbolizes the loss of the kingdom.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 11, 24, 13, 1, 11, 'the man that owneth this girdle', 'Symbolism of the Girdle', 'This connection highlights the use of a girdle as a symbol of binding and relationship. In both passages, the girdle represents a physical and spiritual connection, illustrating the consequences of disobedience and the fate of the people.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 21, 11, 11, 11, 29, 31, 'Thus saith the Holy Ghost', 'Prophetic Acts of Binding', 'Both passages emphasize prophetic actions involving binding. In Acts, the binding of Paul foreshadows his fate, while in 1 Kings, the tearing of the garment symbolizes the division of the kingdom. This connection highlights the use of physical actions to convey divine messages.', 'prophecy', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
